1
00:00:02,714 --> 00:00:19,676
namo tassa bhagavato arhato sammasambuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arhato sammasambuddhasa

2
00:00:19,977 --> 00:00:32,959
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato sambha sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,601 --> 00:00:43,938
I've pre-recorded this moon because I'm on personal retreat at the moment, when you see it anyway.

4
00:00:43,978 --> 00:00:45,039
So last November,

5
00:00:46,234 --> 00:00:53,268
we dedicated this lugubrious month to that regular party topic, death.

6
00:00:55,752 --> 00:01:02,725
And we learned how powerful the Buddha thought the contemplation was leading to full liberation.

7
00:01:04,004 --> 00:01:07,671
Now, this is actually one of a set of five.

8
00:01:08,712 --> 00:01:16,507
And in the numerical sayings, there's a discourse of the five constant or regular contemplations.

9
00:01:19,593 --> 00:01:26,585
For those of you who want to know, it's in the chapter 5, verse 57.

10
00:01:28,590 --> 00:01:34,117
So I'm going to read parts of the discourse and then we're going to look at the different contemplations.

11
00:01:34,557 --> 00:01:34,858
Okay.

12
00:01:36,198 --> 00:01:46,368
So bhikkhus or listeners, the commentary is always gloss bhikkhus to mean anybody who's reading the scriptures.

13
00:01:46,388 --> 00:01:49,373
Yeah.

14
00:01:49,393 --> 00:01:56,379
There are five themes that should often be reflected upon by a woman or a man, by a householder or one gone forth.

15
00:01:56,780 --> 00:01:57,501
What five?

16
00:01:58,897 --> 00:02:02,802
I am subject to aging, I am not exempt from aging.

17
00:02:02,822 --> 00:02:07,608
I am subject to illness, I am not exempt from illness.

18
00:02:08,330 --> 00:02:11,533
I am subject to death, I am not exempt from death.

19
00:02:12,695 --> 00:02:18,923
I must be parted and separated from everyone and everything dear and agreeable to me.

20
00:02:20,324 --> 00:02:25,632
I am the owner of my karma, my actions of body, speech and mind.

21
00:02:26,287 --> 00:02:27,848
I'm heir to my karma.

22
00:02:28,409 --> 00:02:34,580
I have karma as my origin, karma as my relative, karma as my resort.

23
00:02:35,381 --> 00:02:40,788
I will be heir to whatever karma, good or bad, that I do.

24
00:02:43,973 --> 00:02:48,760
I'm going to leave karma till next November because it's a big subject, yeah.

25
00:02:50,984 --> 00:02:53,407
Then he tells us what the benefits are, right?

26
00:02:55,109 --> 00:02:58,414
So what are the benefits to this sort of practice?

27
00:02:59,818 --> 00:03:05,027
First of all, he points out, in a state of health, I am subject to illness.

28
00:03:05,489 --> 00:03:07,032
I'm not exempt from illness.

29
00:03:07,473 --> 00:03:11,881
In a state of health, beings are intoxicated with their health.

30
00:03:11,901 --> 00:03:17,893
And when intoxicated with their health, they engage in misconduct by body, speech and mind.

31
00:03:19,443 --> 00:03:21,205
We often take it for granted.

32
00:03:21,264 --> 00:03:23,287
Sometimes we don't eat properly.

33
00:03:23,847 --> 00:03:28,891
At other times we're a bit obsessed by what we eat, vitamins and so on.

34
00:03:31,275 --> 00:03:32,496
I'm subject to aging.

35
00:03:32,735 --> 00:03:34,098
I'm not exempt from aging.

36
00:03:34,758 --> 00:03:39,763
In their youth, beings are intoxicated with youth.

37
00:03:39,782 --> 00:03:46,530
And when they're intoxicated in their youth, they engage in misconduct by body, speech and mind.

38
00:03:46,509 --> 00:03:51,676
Of course, we live in a very youthful culture, Botox and all that.

39
00:03:52,638 --> 00:03:58,826
And so, you know, we pretend to be youthful until the point where we kick the bucket.

40
00:03:59,647 --> 00:04:01,651
60, as they say, is the new 40.

41
00:04:02,331 --> 00:04:03,393
Such is delusion.

42
00:04:04,955 --> 00:04:06,037
I'm subject to death.

43
00:04:06,957 --> 00:04:08,300
I'm not exempt from death.

44
00:04:08,941 --> 00:04:12,906
During their life, beings are intoxicated with life.

45
00:04:13,072 --> 00:04:19,218
And when they're intoxicated with life, they engage in misconduct of body, speech and mind.

46
00:04:22,180 --> 00:04:27,586
And of course, here we can quote the Buddha's understanding of this contemplation.

47
00:04:28,788 --> 00:04:41,019
Monks, when mindfulness of death, when developed and pursued, is of great fruit, of great benefit, it gains a footing in nirvana, the deathless, has nirvana, the deathless, as its final end.

48
00:04:45,504 --> 00:04:48,290
And then there's the renunciation.

49
00:04:49,492 --> 00:04:54,860
I must be parted and separated from everyone and everything dear and agreeable to me.

50
00:04:55,300 --> 00:05:01,591
And beings have desire and craving in regard to those people and things that are dear and agreeable.

51
00:05:02,492 --> 00:05:09,824
And excited by this craving, they engage in misconduct of my body, speech and mind.

52
00:05:11,172 --> 00:05:15,038
One exercise there that you might take up is to create two lists.

53
00:05:15,319 --> 00:05:17,802
All the things you wouldn't want to lose will be robbed.

54
00:05:18,605 --> 00:05:23,913
And all the people whom you wouldn't what you would miss if they disappeared or died.

55
00:05:25,016 --> 00:05:26,978
So that's a nice little exercise.

56
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:31,526
And then you'll see what to do with them as we go through the discourse.

57
00:05:32,822 --> 00:05:36,750
I'm owner of my karma, my actions of body, speech and mind.

58
00:05:36,769 --> 00:05:39,053
That's what karma here means, not comeuppance.

59
00:05:39,795 --> 00:05:40,776
Heir to my karma.

60
00:05:40,956 --> 00:05:42,259
I've karma as my origin.

61
00:05:42,459 --> 00:05:43,661
Karma is my relative.

62
00:05:43,762 --> 00:05:45,105
Karma is my resort.

63
00:05:45,985 --> 00:05:49,853
I will be heir to whatever karma, good or bad, that I do.

64
00:05:50,625 --> 00:05:54,649
People engage in misconduct by body, speech and mind.

65
00:05:55,370 --> 00:06:04,577
Now, when one often reflects on these themes, such misconduct is diminished or completely abandoned.

66
00:06:05,119 --> 00:06:13,365
And it is for the sake of this benefit that a woman or a man, a householder or one gone forth often reflect thus.

67
00:06:13,565 --> 00:06:19,992
OK, so as you reflect this, these themes lose their power over us.

68
00:06:22,064 --> 00:06:28,973
In the next section, he gives us some indication on how to reflect.

69
00:06:28,994 --> 00:06:35,562
The noble disciple reflects thus, I'm not the only one who is subject to illness, not exempt from illness.

70
00:06:35,884 --> 00:06:41,872
All beings that come and go and pass away and undergo rebirth are all subject to illness.

71
00:06:42,012 --> 00:06:44,035
None are exempt from illness.

72
00:06:44,836 --> 00:06:47,540
So this, in a sense, puts us into the big picture.

73
00:06:47,781 --> 00:06:49,523
So there's nothing special about me.

74
00:06:49,839 --> 00:06:54,906
I may be lucky and not suffer from severe illness, but illness will come my way.

75
00:06:55,608 --> 00:06:59,012
And if it is to be, well, I shall have to just accept it.

76
00:07:02,478 --> 00:07:08,745
The noble disciple reflects thus, I'm not the only one subject to ageing or exempt from ageing.

77
00:07:08,766 --> 00:07:13,112
All beings that come and go, that pass away and undergo rebirth are subject to ageing.

78
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:16,336
None are exempt from ageing.

79
00:07:17,447 --> 00:07:26,776
So again, there's a sort of, or at least I feel, a strange comfort in knowing that all of us go through this process of aging.

80
00:07:26,817 --> 00:07:30,040
In fact, all beings go through this process of aging.

81
00:07:31,422 --> 00:07:36,906
A noble disciple reflects thus, I'm not the only one who's subject to death, not exempt from death.

82
00:07:37,348 --> 00:07:42,052
All beings that come and go, that pass away and undergo rebirth are subject to death.

83
00:07:42,273 --> 00:07:44,194
None are exempt from death.

84
00:07:45,175 --> 00:07:46,137
Now, that's interesting.

85
00:07:46,177 --> 00:07:46,576
I mean,

86
00:07:47,182 --> 00:07:55,709
You know, when both my mother and father and all that generation had passed away some 20 odd years ago, maybe 30 years.

87
00:07:55,730 --> 00:07:57,351
It's a strange comfort, you know.

88
00:07:57,372 --> 00:08:02,916
I mean, these people that were so close to you, they've gone through that process.

89
00:08:03,598 --> 00:08:06,701
And so it makes it easier for us to do so.

90
00:08:06,721 --> 00:08:12,987
I mean, can you imagine what it would be like if you were the first person to die?

91
00:08:15,785 --> 00:08:22,831
It reminds me of a cartoon I saw once where there's an elderly lady on her deathbed surrounded by her friends.

92
00:08:23,012 --> 00:08:24,894
And she says, why me?

93
00:08:25,254 --> 00:08:26,276
Why not one of you?

94
00:08:26,315 --> 00:08:40,509
I'm not the only one who must be parted and separated from everyone and everything dear to and pleasing to me.

95
00:08:41,249 --> 00:08:50,123
All beings that come and go, that pass away and undergo rebirth must be parted and separated from everyone and everything dear and pleasing.

96
00:08:50,744 --> 00:08:55,851
So this is really about renunciation, about letting go before you have to let go.

97
00:08:55,873 --> 00:09:00,539
I mean, take an instance where a robber takes your mobile.

98
00:09:01,128 --> 00:09:06,917
You see, you go around angry and moaning about the state of affairs and all that.

99
00:09:07,037 --> 00:09:10,822
And this thief has got my mobile.

100
00:09:11,264 --> 00:09:13,927
But it's not my mobile anymore, is it?

101
00:09:14,067 --> 00:09:15,090
It belongs to the thief.

102
00:09:16,913 --> 00:09:26,528
So he's able to sort of let that go and wish that the thief benefits from his theft in some positive way or at least puts it to good use.

103
00:09:26,648 --> 00:09:26,847
Yeah.

104
00:09:31,638 --> 00:09:48,551
And finally, I'm not the only one who is owner of my karma, heir to my karma, who has karma as one's origin, karma as one's relative, karma as one's resort, who will be heir to whatever karma they do, bad or good.

105
00:09:49,092 --> 00:09:53,881
All beings that come and go, pass away and undergo rebirth are owners of their karma.

106
00:09:57,759 --> 00:10:10,374
And as they often reflect on these themes, okay, so all these things, as they often reflect on these themes, they pursue the path, develop it and cultivate it.

107
00:10:11,936 --> 00:10:20,986
And as they do so, the fetters are entirely abandoned and the underlying tendencies are uprooted.

108
00:10:21,788 --> 00:10:25,692
Okay, so this is also a path to liberation.

109
00:10:26,717 --> 00:10:28,124
Now, what are the fetters?

110
00:10:28,264 --> 00:10:36,980
The fetters or the chains or whatever, the manacles that keep us into this process of rebirth, the first three

111
00:10:37,129 --> 00:10:45,720
The view of self, skeptical doubt and clinging to rites and rituals or just thinking that rites and rituals are enough.

112
00:10:45,840 --> 00:10:51,806
You know, light 100,000 candles to the Buddha and you're bound to be liberated.

113
00:10:52,226 --> 00:10:53,447
That sort of understanding.

114
00:10:53,849 --> 00:10:59,695
That goes when a person enters the first level of attainment stream entry.

115
00:11:01,379 --> 00:11:09,529
But the other two don't go until you're at the third level, which is the non-returner, because they've lost any desire for this sort of dwelling.

116
00:11:10,390 --> 00:11:15,057
And that sensual craving and ill will have been done away with.

117
00:11:16,198 --> 00:11:30,778
But the last five, craving for the joys of the lower five absorptions and of the upper four absorptions, those two, they go first.

118
00:11:31,078 --> 00:11:33,643
Not the jhana, just a craving for it.

119
00:11:34,484 --> 00:11:40,933
Then there's the conceit, right, which is always about comparison, better than, worse than, equal to.

120
00:11:40,974 --> 00:11:54,014
Restlessness, which suggests that right to the point of liberation, there's always a bit of defilements there, the little end defilements which cause restlessness of one level or another.

121
00:11:55,895 --> 00:11:56,918
And, of course, ignorance.

122
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:09,292
The Anusaya are the subconscious tendencies which come up whenever there's a when it's prompted by circumstance.

123
00:12:09,773 --> 00:12:11,413
So we don't actually know what's down there.

124
00:12:11,554 --> 00:12:11,774
Right.

125
00:12:11,815 --> 00:12:13,076
This is very Freudian.

126
00:12:13,096 --> 00:12:15,057
Yeah.

127
00:12:15,077 --> 00:12:22,686
But even all that is cleared so that there's no negativity, no defilement within the system.

128
00:12:24,488 --> 00:12:25,708
So I'll just repeat that.

129
00:12:26,429 --> 00:12:39,927
If we continue this meditation, continue these contemplations, excuse me, contemplations, and we'll talk about that in a minute, we will pursue the path and cultivate it.

130
00:12:40,888 --> 00:12:47,556
And as we do so, the fetters are entirely abandoned and the underlying tendencies are uprooted.

131
00:12:47,755 --> 00:12:50,799
In other words, we'll be liberated from all suffering.

132
00:12:52,383 --> 00:12:58,971
Now, at the end, we have a verse which is given to the Buddha.

133
00:13:00,994 --> 00:13:11,467
What I've done is I've retranslated it into ordinary sentences, because the people who translate these verses try to keep it as a verse, and I just find it confusing.

134
00:13:11,868 --> 00:13:15,352
But if you put it into ordinary, straightforward language, it's very simple.

135
00:13:15,738 --> 00:13:22,668
It terrifies ordinary people to contemplate sickness, aging and death and that they are inescapable.

136
00:13:23,009 --> 00:13:23,590
That's true.

137
00:13:25,351 --> 00:13:31,761
If I find myself detesting such people, it would not be proper for me, for I have the same flaws.

138
00:13:33,163 --> 00:13:45,221
Contemplating this while knowing that there is no acquisition, you can't take anything with you to Nibbana, I overcame these obsessions with health, youth and even life.

139
00:13:46,534 --> 00:13:48,597
I saw safety in renunciation.

140
00:13:48,999 --> 00:13:53,765
So I put effort into the practice and realized nibbana.

141
00:13:53,785 --> 00:13:57,451
It is no longer possible for me to indulge in sensual pleasures.

142
00:13:58,351 --> 00:14:03,078
Now that I fulfill the spiritual path, I shall never come back.

143
00:14:04,721 --> 00:14:10,210
So this does suggest that it's not only, of course, these practices.

144
00:14:10,230 --> 00:14:13,234
These practices lead you to develop the path.

145
00:14:13,619 --> 00:14:17,224
And part of that path is, of course, insight meditation.

146
00:14:19,506 --> 00:14:19,606
Okay.

147
00:14:19,626 --> 00:14:21,450
So let's look at how we do this, right?

148
00:14:21,529 --> 00:14:24,594
This wise reflection, as the Buddha would put it.

149
00:14:24,673 --> 00:14:28,798
You always get this little phrase every so often.

150
00:14:29,900 --> 00:14:32,203
So now, first of all, contemplation isn't thinking.

151
00:14:32,244 --> 00:14:42,697
There's a bit of thought involved, but what we're really doing is not an intellectual exercise, but opening up to our feelings about things, our relationship to these things.

152
00:14:43,149 --> 00:14:46,153
five contemplations.

153
00:14:46,173 --> 00:14:47,674
And we have to try and accept something.

154
00:14:47,735 --> 00:14:49,657
Something can be quite difficult for us.

155
00:14:49,797 --> 00:14:53,240
Sometimes it actually stings, yeah?

156
00:14:53,259 --> 00:15:00,388
And you choose a phrase or a passage and you just gently repeat it into the heart, just allowing the heart to accept it, right?

157
00:15:00,467 --> 00:15:04,572
Feel the resistance, keep saying it, keep saying it till you get a surrender.

158
00:15:05,332 --> 00:15:09,596
Then there comes this sense of relief and with it you get a smile.

159
00:15:11,803 --> 00:15:24,395
So you repeat it quietly into the heart, stay with the heart's reaction, wait for the resistance to disappear and wait for it to be digested.

160
00:15:26,197 --> 00:15:29,740
So just to give some idea, you can make up your own phrases.

161
00:15:30,061 --> 00:15:31,842
So these are taken from the scriptures.

162
00:15:31,863 --> 00:15:32,082
Yeah.

163
00:15:32,764 --> 00:15:36,366
So sickness, of course, is sort of mini death or a preparation from death.

164
00:15:36,908 --> 00:15:39,009
The body manifests its vulnerability.

165
00:15:39,344 --> 00:15:46,312
There's discomfort and pain and always some disability, you know, staying in bed or something.

166
00:15:46,332 --> 00:15:47,774
Sickness is unpreventable.

167
00:15:48,556 --> 00:15:50,518
This body is subject to disease.

168
00:15:50,798 --> 00:15:53,162
This body is of a nature to fall ill.

169
00:15:53,722 --> 00:15:58,649
This body has not gone beyond sickness.

170
00:15:58,668 --> 00:16:03,875
So now when you think about that, you see, you think to yourself, OK, subject to disease.

171
00:16:04,596 --> 00:16:06,379
So diseases come to mind.

172
00:16:06,859 --> 00:16:08,041
What am I afraid of?

173
00:16:08,061 --> 00:16:08,861
What am I afraid of?

174
00:16:09,178 --> 00:16:11,061
Is it cancer?

175
00:16:12,043 --> 00:16:13,364
Is it a wasting disease?

176
00:16:14,645 --> 00:16:15,647
Is it dementia?

177
00:16:16,688 --> 00:16:21,875
In one of those, somewhere on the line, there'll be something that you're really afraid of happening, yeah?

178
00:16:21,894 --> 00:16:23,677
And you stick with that.

179
00:16:23,697 --> 00:16:26,240
I am subject to disease.

180
00:16:26,421 --> 00:16:31,167
That doesn't mean you'll wish yourself getting it, right?

181
00:16:31,187 --> 00:16:33,090
Don't frighten yourself out of your skin, you know?

182
00:16:33,590 --> 00:16:38,697
It's just the case of facing these inner demons, these inner fears.

183
00:16:38,962 --> 00:16:44,150
And we've all, all of us suffer to some degree, a bit of hypochondria.

184
00:16:44,331 --> 00:16:44,532
Yeah.

185
00:16:47,155 --> 00:16:53,105
Aging, the contemplation of aging undermines this intoxication with youth, you know, always wanted to be young.

186
00:16:53,725 --> 00:16:55,168
So aging is inevitable.

187
00:16:55,467 --> 00:16:57,191
The body is subject to aging.

188
00:16:58,111 --> 00:16:59,715
Body's not gone beyond aging.

189
00:17:00,174 --> 00:17:02,259
This body is now in a process of aging.

190
00:17:02,860 --> 00:17:06,404
So some, one of those are a phrase you personally make up.

191
00:17:06,654 --> 00:17:07,596
You just repeat it.

192
00:17:07,875 --> 00:17:09,979
This body is now in a process of aging.

193
00:17:10,138 --> 00:17:10,859
What does that mean?

194
00:17:10,900 --> 00:17:13,582
You say this process of aging.

195
00:17:14,182 --> 00:17:17,707
So I'm looking at my skin and my strength.

196
00:17:18,867 --> 00:17:19,949
Yeah.

197
00:17:19,969 --> 00:17:22,451
How my relationship changes.

198
00:17:23,373 --> 00:17:23,613
So.

199
00:17:25,775 --> 00:17:27,156
Now, the big one, of course, is death.

200
00:17:28,018 --> 00:17:29,298
So life is uncertain.

201
00:17:29,318 --> 00:17:30,440
Death is certain.

202
00:17:30,641 --> 00:17:30,901
Right.

203
00:17:31,642 --> 00:17:34,704
Sometimes saying the obvious sort of hits the nail on the head, you know.

204
00:17:35,916 --> 00:17:44,968
So this undermines clinging to life at all costs, barricading it with fame, riches and power, no matter how little we might have of them.

205
00:17:44,988 --> 00:17:47,230
So death is inescapable.

206
00:17:47,250 --> 00:17:49,012
Everyone must die.

207
00:17:49,452 --> 00:17:53,377
The remainder of my lifespan is decreasing continually.

208
00:17:54,798 --> 00:17:58,683
Death will come regardless of weather.

209
00:17:58,748 --> 00:18:01,892
I have made time to practice the Dharma.

210
00:18:02,272 --> 00:18:05,376
That can be a bit terrifying, that one.

211
00:18:06,317 --> 00:18:09,080
We don't know when we're going to die, okay?

212
00:18:09,821 --> 00:18:13,125
Human life expectancy is uncertain.

213
00:18:13,807 --> 00:18:15,869
There are many causes for death.

214
00:18:16,691 --> 00:18:18,773
The human body is fragile.

215
00:18:20,336 --> 00:18:24,000
Only the practice of Dharma can help us at the time of our death.

216
00:18:24,080 --> 00:18:25,321
Now, there's a bit of comfort.

217
00:18:25,923 --> 00:18:26,763
There's a bit of comfort.

218
00:18:27,317 --> 00:18:31,625
Only the practice of Dharma can help us at the hour of our death.

219
00:18:33,068 --> 00:18:34,510
Our wealth cannot help us.

220
00:18:34,612 --> 00:18:36,154
Our loved ones cannot help us.

221
00:18:36,776 --> 00:18:38,278
Even our own body cannot help us.

222
00:18:38,880 --> 00:18:40,963
So death is inescapable.

223
00:18:41,364 --> 00:18:43,107
This body is subject to death.

224
00:18:43,749 --> 00:18:45,392
This body is not gone beyond death.

225
00:18:45,471 --> 00:18:47,115
This body will die.

226
00:18:50,250 --> 00:19:05,971
So basically, it's like when you're trying to get a situation where, you know, such as a doctor who tells you you've got a very serious disease or it's a terminal illness, you know, and you're just sitting there with that and you keep repeating it.

227
00:19:06,010 --> 00:19:06,731
Just keep repeating.

228
00:19:06,751 --> 00:19:10,195
You just feel how it is to say something like this body.

229
00:19:10,536 --> 00:19:11,597
This body will die.

230
00:19:12,117 --> 00:19:13,279
You get in touch with the body.

231
00:19:13,299 --> 00:19:13,901
You feel it.

232
00:19:14,601 --> 00:19:16,022
You see it in your mind's eye.

233
00:19:16,584 --> 00:19:19,126
This body will die.

234
00:19:20,811 --> 00:19:23,877
This body, this body will go.

235
00:19:24,719 --> 00:19:24,900
Yeah.

236
00:19:27,464 --> 00:19:33,015
In the same way, I must be parted and separated from everyone and everything dear and agreeable to me.

237
00:19:33,095 --> 00:19:41,570
So this is, again, making those two lists, you know, and just just recognizing the things you really don't want to let go of.

238
00:19:41,651 --> 00:19:43,173
But they're going to let go of you.

239
00:19:44,825 --> 00:19:48,871
And then finally, something we won't go into this evening is karma.

240
00:19:49,092 --> 00:19:50,953
I'm owner of my karma actions.

241
00:19:51,474 --> 00:19:55,622
Karma here, remember, means actions, not comeuppance.

242
00:19:56,542 --> 00:19:58,486
I inherit the results of my actions.

243
00:19:58,645 --> 00:20:00,028
I'm born of my actions.

244
00:20:00,128 --> 00:20:02,231
I form relations through my actions.

245
00:20:02,672 --> 00:20:03,053
I live.

246
00:20:03,488 --> 00:20:08,494
dependent on my actions, whatever good or bad I do, I shall inherit those results.

247
00:20:08,836 --> 00:20:13,363
Now, we can still contemplate that by just repeating a phrase which touches us.

248
00:20:13,943 --> 00:20:18,830
You're always looking for a phrase which touches you, which sort of hits the button.

249
00:20:20,814 --> 00:20:24,078
But we'll go into that in more detail next November.

250
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:25,461
Okay.

251
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:25,580
Okay.

252
00:20:27,248 --> 00:20:38,146
So what I've done is I put this up as a PDF, the actual original discourse with all these exercises, which you can download.

253
00:20:38,708 --> 00:20:46,261
The video won't go up, nor the actual spoken won't go up until I return in December.

254
00:20:46,701 --> 00:20:52,092
So in this case, it doesn't really matter because here you've got the exercises that you can do.

255
00:20:55,295 --> 00:20:56,256
Very good.

256
00:20:56,316 --> 00:21:05,008
I can't think of any other way more skillful to spend this lugubrious November.

257
00:21:06,690 --> 00:21:15,260
I wish that your practice of these five reflections will lead you speedily along the path of liberation.

